AU  - Swamy, P.A.V.B.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 14
IS  - 2
SP  - 161
EP  - 181
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/10/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(80)90088-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407680900883
AB  - An important justification for the Swamy-Holmes (1971) approach lies in the non-contradiction that it imposes on the method of analysis of undersized samples using different restrictions on the structural and reduced forms. When the samples are undersized, there is the problem of lack of determinability of reduced form parameters unless sufficient a priori restrictions are imposed. The non-contradiction principle postulated in this paper demands that the restrictions imposed on the reduced form parameters should not contradict the identifying restrictions imposed on the structure. The non-Bayesian alternatives to the Swamy-Holmes solution are unsatisfactory when judge by this principle.
ER  - 

